{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17615160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17615160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:51:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:51:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16380"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7102"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"},{"type":"tags","id":"10367"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21567"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures are primarily connected by the anterior commissure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parietal lobes","Temporal lobes","Occipital lobes","Frontal lobes","Cerebellar hemispheres"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior commissure is a bundle of white matter fibres that crosses the midline of the brain anterior to the fornix and connects primarily the temporal lobes between hemispheres. It also carries fibres connecting olfactory structures between the two sides of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal lobes\u003C/strong\u003E are indeed connected via the anterior commissure, which allows for interhemispheric communication particularly important for memory, emotion, and auditory processing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal lobes\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily connected via the corpus callosum, particularly its posterior portion, not the anterior commissure. The parietal lobes are important for sensory integration and spatial awareness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital lobes\u003C/strong\u003E communicate via the splenium of the corpus callosum, which is crucial for coordinating visual information between hemispheres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile some anterior commissure fibres may reach portions of the \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal lobes\u003C/strong\u003E, these are primarily connected via the genu and anterior body of the corpus callosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar hemispheres\u003C/strong\u003E are connected by the cerebellar commissure and vermis, not by the anterior commissure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The anterior commissure connects the temporal lobes and olfactory structures between hemispheres.","While smaller than the corpus callosum, the anterior commissure is an important white matter tract for interhemispheric communication.","The anterior commissure is preserved in patients who undergo corpus callosotomy for epilepsy."],"references":["Baudo MC, Colombo EE, P\u00e9rez MA, Rahn SI, Domenech NC, Chuang J, Forlizzi V, Buosi P, Baldoncini M, Bendersky M. Three-Dimensional Anatomy of the Anterior Commissure: A Tractography and Anatomical Study. World Neurosurg. 2022 Mar;159:e365-e374. doi: 10.1016/j.wneu.2021.12.059. Epub 2021 Dec 21. PMID: 34952222.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T20:52:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T21:48:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[]